Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Statement of  the Problem", "TechNoteSection",
 CellID->3657172,ExpressionUUID->"4bce2c8d-8f1d-4cc7-9a5c-5d3470310b1f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Consider a classical function ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"f", ":", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], "n"], "\[RightArrow]", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"4cfb10b7-62f4-4a0b-90e9-6451b53f9799"],
 ". It is a classical oracle taking ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d24817a0-4831-46bd-93b4-98df212fae82"],
 "-bit inputs and returning 0 or 1. The function is promised to be either \
constant (either 0 or 1 for all inputs) or balanced (0 for one half of the \
possible inputs and 1 for the other half). The task is to determine whether f \
is constant or balanced by using the oracle the least number of times."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1336547688,ExpressionUUID->"34ac1d50-2043-4efc-86cc-f37779dda39c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In classical algorithms, one has to evaluate the oracle ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox["2", 
       RowBox[{"n", "-", "1"}]], "+", "1"}], ")"}], "\[TildeTilde]", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox["2", "n"], "/", "2"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "02c5b32f-7867-47de-85c9-7219380ca69b"],
 " times in the worst case. That is, one has to try almost half of the \
possible inputs before reliably determining the unknown property of the \
oracle. As we will see now, the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm determines the \
property from a single query to the ",
 ButtonBox["quantum oracle",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumOracle"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->678044596,ExpressionUUID->"1924870a-4e98-409b-b090-5533d0b2bda5"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Quantum Implementation", "TechNoteSection",
 CellID->1347293990,ExpressionUUID->"3c81b9af-40dc-4c85-ab29-b30133d05583"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The quantum circuit in Figure 1 summarizes the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm. The \
last qubit is an ancillary qubit that induces the conditional phase shifts on \
the first ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b004ee34-7381-448b-8c6d-220805d23267"],
 " qubits. The Hadamard gate on it ensures that the ancillary qubit is in the \
eigenstate ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{"-"},
     "Ket"], ":=", 
    FractionBox[
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{"0"},
       "Ket"], "-", 
      TemplateBox[{"1"},
       "Ket"]}], 
     SqrtBox["2"]]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2d465922-d59a-4778-9c19-7eb8e4298583"],
 " of the Pauli X operator just before the quantum oracle operates."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->902515962,ExpressionUUID->"c0b440d0-07a4-435e-8b88-0b418a7fbf16"],

